"   <div id=\"basicsTopicLeft\">",
"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Gastroparesis (delayed gastric emptying) (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/gastroparesis-delayed-gastric-emptying-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2420075\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is gastroparesis?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Gastroparesis is a condition that causes nausea and vomiting. It can also make you feel full too soon after you start eating. It happens because the stomach takes too long to empty and does not move food along through your body fast enough (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef66110 \" href=\"UTD.htm?28/27/29107\">",
"       figure 1",
"      </a>",
"      ). Gastroparesis is also called &ldquo;delayed gastric emptying.&rdquo; (&ldquo;Gastric&rdquo; means &ldquo;having to do with the stomach.&rdquo;)",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Gastroparesis is a common problem among people with diabetes. It also can happen to people who have had food poisoning (gastroenteritis). But it can also happen to people who have not been sick and who do not have diabetes.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      When gastroparesis starts after someone has had food poisoning, it often gets better in a few days to weeks. Sometimes it lasts longer or never goes away. In people with diabetes, it usually does not go away, but there are things that can make it better.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2420082\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of gastroparesis?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The symptoms can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Nausea with or without vomiting",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Belly pain",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Feeling full too soon after you start eating",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Bloating (feeling as though your stomach is full of air)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Weight loss",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2420089\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there a test for gastroparesis?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. If your doctor or nurse suspects you have gastroparesis, he or she might do 1 or more of these tests:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        <strong>",
"         Endoscopy",
"        </strong>",
"        &ndash; To prepare for an endoscopy, you eat normally the day before the test but eat nothing the day of the test. For the test, a doctor or nurse puts a thin tube down your throat and into your stomach. The tube (called an endoscope) has a light and a tiny camera on the end, so it allows the doctor or nurse to see inside your stomach. If he or she still finds food in your stomach even though it has been more than 8 hours since you ate, that is a sign that you might have gastroparesis.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?18/37/19028?source=see_link\">",
"         Barium",
"        </a>",
"        <strong>",
"         swallow",
"        </strong>",
"        &ndash; For this test you eat a special meal that shows up on X-ray. Then you have X-rays taken to see how long it takes for the food to leave your stomach.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        <strong>",
"         Gastric emptying scintigraphy",
"        </strong>",
"        &ndash; For this test you eat food that has a small amount of a radioactive material in it. Then you have images taken of the inside of your body every hour for 4 hours. That way, doctors can follow where the food goes and how fast it gets there. If you still have a fair amount of food in your stomach after 4 hours, that means you have gastroparesis.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2420096\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there anything I can do on my own to feel better?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. Some people feel better if they:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Eat several small meals during the day instead of 2 or 3 big ones.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Cut down on foods that have a lot of fat, such as cheese and fried foods.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Cut down on foods that have a lot of fiber, such as fruits, vegetables, and beans.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If you have diabetes, it&rsquo;s also very important to keep your blood sugar as close to normal as possible.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2420103\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Should I see a doctor or nurse?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;See your doctor or nurse if you have ongoing nausea or vomiting, belly pain, trouble eating, or weight loss.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2420110\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is gastroparesis treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Treatments can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        <strong>",
"         Treatments to help you get the food and fluids you need",
"        </strong>",
"        &ndash; This might include taking liquid food supplements or&mdash;in rare cases&mdash;being fed through a tube.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        <strong>",
"         Medicines that make the stomach empty faster",
"        </strong>",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        <strong>",
"         Medicines that help prevent nausea",
"        </strong>",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        <strong>",
"         Emptying the stomach with a tube &ndash;",
"        </strong>",
"        To do this, doctors can put a tube down your throat or directly into your stomach through your skin.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
